For a score and ten, the wolves terrorised our village. They ravaged our livestock, and when there were no animals left, they stole our children. We lived in fear of the darkness, but that all changed in the Autumn. The Inquisition swept through our small hamlet, hundreds strong. They were here but 3 days when they dragged Old Marvin the drunk into the street and set him ablaze.

We watched in horror as he changed from human to beast and back again. He had been the Alpha of the pack, now with him dead the Inquisition made swift work of the rest. Some ran, while others pled for their lives, agreeing to serve the whims of the village.

Soon enough our saviours become our captors. They had come in search of heretics, and here they were found. They slaughtered our Seers and those that had Protected us before. They disbanded our Militia, and imposed their own laws arresting anyone who had magical inclinations. We stashed our runes and totems, our family heirlooms. The ones we couldn’t hide were destroyed in the village square.

That winter was the harshest we’ve known. Our crops withered and died in the field. The local wildlife abandoned the area for warmer climes, and as always, the hunters followed their prey. With no meat or grain available, the inquisition finally left. They took with them anything of use, weapons & armours, potions & salves. They left us worse off than the wolves ever did, broken and humiliated in a few short weeks. There are those who mourn the Pack in the wake of what came after, though most of us are glad they’re gone.

Finally, Spring arrived and with it came new found hope. The animals returned and the ground thawed. Travellers arrived bringing with them, fresh supplies and new friends. The most recent arrivals seem pleasant enough, although there’s something odd about them. I swear they look different every time I see them...
